<p>Keeper is a machine provided by HackTheBox. After you log into the platform you need to instantiate the machine and then add the provided IP in your /etc/hosts/ file as follows:</p>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">[ip] keeper.htb</div>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">[ip] tickets.keeper.htb</div>

<p>Now you can navigate to the first one and you&#39;ll be redirected to the second one.</p>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="height:456px; width:612px" /></p>

<p>The application shows us this login page and, after some Google research, I notice that is the login of <a href="https://bestpractical.com/request-tracker">RT Best Practical</a>.</p>

<p>The exposed version is outdated and the default credentials are publicly available.</p>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">username: root</div>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">password: password</div>

<p>Once We have logged in We have a lot of functionalities, so I start to inspect every one to discover something new.</p>

<p>Starting from the <strong>Admin</strong> menu We can quickly identify the <strong>Users</strong> submenu where We can find every signed user.</p>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>

<p>Let&#39;s see if there is some interesting information in the <strong>lnorgaard</strong> user.</p>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>

<p>The screenshot above shows that this user has a <strong>Unix Login</strong> and a comment reveals the user&#39;s password. So now We have a set of Unix credentials, let&#39;s try to open a shell using ssh.</p>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>

<p>VERY NICE! We have successfully established a ssh connection and got the first flag. But We want to escalate until root so let&#39;s keep going.</p>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">User&#39;s flag: <strong>b8c7c38b98c11be50180a8662572b006</strong></div>

<p>With the flag, We got a file RT30000.zip, using the <strong>scp</strong> command We can easily download this file.</p>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">scp lnorgaard@[IP]:/home/lnorgaard/RT30000.zip .</div>

<p>This file contains other two files <strong>KeePassDumpFull.dmp</strong> and <strong>passcodes.kdbx</strong>. The first one is a Keepass memory dump and may contain the master password while the second one is a Keepass database that, if We can unlock it, may contain the root password or some other details to go forward.</p>

<p>First of all, this kind of memory dump is vulnerable to a CVE, specifically to <a href="https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/cve-2023-32784">CVE-2023-32784</a>. After some Google research, I&#39;ve got a PoC written in Python.</p>

<p><a href="https://github.com/matro7sh/keepass-dump-masterkey">Here</a> you can find the PoC repository.</p>

<p>I run the PoC and then show you the result below:</p>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>

<p>The result seems to don&#39;t provide any useful information but if We google the resulting password We get a page of a Danish dessert. If you remember (otherwise return above to the user&#39;s information) our user is Danish.</p>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>

<p>So, let&#39;s try to unlock the Keepass password database with some combinations of different char case of the dessert&#39;s name, follows a word list that I&#39;ve create from the original name:</p>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">R&oslash;dgr&oslash;d Med Fl&oslash;de</div>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">R&oslash;dgr&oslash;d_Med_Fl&oslash;de</div>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">R&oslash;dgr&oslash;dMedFl&oslash;de</div>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">RodgrodMedFlode</div>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">r&oslash;dgr&oslash;d med fl&oslash;de</div>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">r&oslash;dgr&oslash;d_med_fl&oslash;de</div>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">r&oslash;dgr&oslash;dmedfl&oslash;de</div>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">rodgrodmedflode</div>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">r0dgr0dm3dfl0d3</div>

<p>And as expected the password is <strong>r&oslash;dgr&oslash;d med fl&oslash;de.</strong></p>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>

<p>If We try to establish the ssh session for the root user using the password it won&#39;t work. But in the note, We can clearly see a <strong>PuTTY-User-Key-File-3</strong> content.</p>

<p>Putty is a software used in Windows to implement the ssh protocol (Yes Windows doesn&#39;t support it natively). Sometimes Putty generates a <strong>ppk</strong> file that contains a kind of rsa key exactly as the pem file in Linux.</p>

<p>Fortunately, <strong>openssl</strong> provides a way to convert <strong>ppk</strong> files into <strong>pem</strong> files. Let&#39;s save the code in a file <strong>ppk_file.ppk</strong> and run the following command:</p>

<pre>
<code>openssl pkcs8 -inform DER -in ppk_file.ppk -outform PEM -out pem_file.pem </code></pre>

<p>&nbsp;With the pem_file.pem We can establish our ssh shell for root as follows:</p>

<div style="background:#eeeeee; border:1px solid #cccccc; padding:5px 10px; color: black;">ssh -i pem_file.pem root@[IP]</div>
